# Git, Job, and AI Runner Rules

## Git / Worktree Rules

- AI work must run in a request-specific Git worktree, not in the main working directory.
- Never modify the default branch or currently checked-out branch directly for AI jobs.
- Create detached worktrees from the current `HEAD` of the requested project repository.
- Let users specify a branch name; otherwise generate a safe slug plus timestamp.
- If there are no changes, do not create a branch, commit, or push.
- If changes exist, create a branch, commit, then push to the configured remote (`origin` by default).
- Collect changed files before commit and store them in the job result.
- Automatic commit messages must use `type: title`, bullet body lines, and `committed by remote-coder: <job-id>`.
- The title must summarize the functional change, not copy the user's raw request.
- The first bullet must describe what the AI agent changed, not list recent files or repeat the prompt.
- Store commit hash, branch name, and changed files in the job result.
- Make worktree cleanup/preservation behavior explicit and configurable.
- `/monitor branch` summarizes branch lists and counts.
- `/branch` shows the current branch.
- `/branch <name>` switches only to an existing local branch in the project bound to the current bot instance.
- `/rebase`, `/clear`, and other broad Git/state-changing commands must run only when the user explicitly calls them.

## Job Rules

- Every job must have a unique Job ID.
- Job state must support at least `queued`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, and `cancelled`.
- Apply per-job timeouts.
- Record the stage where a failure occurred.
- Store commit hash, branch name, changed files, observed detailed model name, and token usage when available.
- Store job result summaries in SQLite conversation memory, including observed model and token usage when available.

## AI Runner Rules

- Claude, Codex, and Gemini execution must sit behind a shared runner interface.
- Runner input should include instruction text, working directory, timeout, and environment.
- Runner output should include stdout, stderr, exit code, start time, and end time.
- Extract detailed model name and token usage from CLI logs when observable and store them as structured fields.
- Build subprocess arguments as lists, not shell-joined strings.
- Always set `cwd` and timeout explicitly.
- Keep runner selection behind Strategy or Factory so model conditionals do not spread through services.
- Wrap Claude/Codex/Gemini CLI details in adapters so domain logic does not depend on subprocess specifics.
